@kbuzzard @eric-wieser

More precisely; you should not run `lake update` if you are working on mathlib itself; you should run `git pull origin master`
Hi Eric! I have messed up my codes by mistake. Now there are too many errors. Is there any way I can erase the former codes and download mathlib4 again?
Just revert the last commit, which you can do with `git revert HEAD`
But I guess I have made a mistake: I have run `git pull origin master` before running `git revert HEAD`. Now it seems that the situation is hard to deal with. How can I resolve this issue?
You can do `git reset --hard 89d042b46480948b15e77cdca758798cb5cce2bd` to take things back to where you were before you changed this file, then `git push -f`

I have successfully returned to the previous commit (the one before I ran `lake update`) and I have run `git pull origin master`, but no file compiles anymore. The error message is:
```
`/Users/lifangming/.elan/toolchains/leanprover--lean4---v4.2.0-rc1/bin/lake print-paths Init Mathlib.GroupTheory.MonoidLocalization Mathlib.RingTheory.NonZeroDivisors Mathlib.RingTheory.OreLocalization.OreSet Mathlib.Tactic.NoncommRing` failed:
...

has type

error: external command `/Users/lifangming/.elan/toolchains/leanprover--lean4---v4.2.0-rc1/bin/lean` exited with code 1
```
Is it because the version of mathlib4 I have right now is incorrect?
After you run `git pull origin master`, you should push your change. Once CI is happy, you'll be able to run `lake exe cache get` and everything should be happy again.
I have pushed my change, but it still cannot pass CI.

That's because you need to fix your code! The merge went just fine, but you nee to deal with the fact that mathlib is not the same as it was when you started.

 The last commit you pushed just deleted all your code; you should revert it.

This has been renamed to

```suggestion
variable [DecidableEq ι] [CanonicallyOrderedAddCommMonoid ι]
```
Why did you change this file?
Similarly here, you should not need to change this

It was very strange. Originally The file Mathlib/NumberTheory/Dioph.lean had some errors. Lean4 gave me some suggestions on how to change the codes. Hence I followed the suggestions. But then there were some merge conflicts.
I would guess that the issues in downstream files are caused by adding this import. I suggest you put the `IsNoetherianRing` result in a new `GradedAlgebra.Noetherian` file.

Does this or similar work?
```suggestion
  neg_mem' hx := neg_mem hx
```
Yeah this works.

```suggestion
  add_mem' a1 a2 := add_mem a1 a2
```
Yeah this works. Thanks!

```suggestion
  mul_mem' a b ha hb := by
```

No this doesn't work. I have tried to change my codes according to what you said, but it resulted in an error:
```
type mismatch
  fun a b ha hb ↦ ?m.460700 a b ha hb
has type
  (a : a✝ ∈ ↑(A 0)) →
    (b : b✝ ∈ ↑(A 0)) →
      (ha : ?m.460697 a b) → (hb : ?m.460698 a b ha) → ?m.460699 a b ha hb : Sort (imax ?u.460688 ?u.460691 ?u.460694)
but is expected to have type
  a✝ ∈ ↑(A 0) → b✝ ∈ ↑(A 0) → a✝ * b✝ ∈ ↑(A 0) : Prop
the following variables have been introduced by the implicit lambda feature
  a✝ : R
  b✝ : R
you can disable implicit lambdas using `@` or writing a lambda expression with `{}` or `[]` binder annotations.
```
looks like a and b are implicit -- try `mul_mem' ha hb := by`?
Or alternatively, `mul_mem' {a b} ha hb := by`, as the error message is alluding to.
Yeah now it works! Thank you very much!
You're not actually using this order, right? I think `AddMonoid` would be sufficient here.
Yeah, `AddMonoid` is enough!

```suggestion
variable (A : ι → σ) [SetLike.GradedMonoid A]
```
(untested)
I've changed it to `SetLike.GradedMonoid A`.
There's no need to have this definition, its the same as the one further up.
Yeah, it is unnecessary. I have deleted the definition and the whole section related to it.
Don't forget to push!

```suggestion
  mul_mem' ha hb := add_zero (0 : ι) ▸ SetLike.mul_mem_graded ha hb
```

```suggestion
instance GradeZero.instSemiring : Semiring (A 0) := (GradeZero.subsemiring A).toSemiring
```

```suggestion
The semiring `A 0` inherited from `R` in the presence of `SetLike.GradedMonoid A`.
```

nit:
```suggestion
def GradedRing.projZeroRingHom' : A →+* 𝒜 0 :=
```
@FMLJohn: I took the liberty of adding the `Comm` versions and the `Algebra` instance.
Oh I see! Nice!

@FMLJohn: whenever you write a new instance, you should write lemmas like this (proven with `rfl`) that characterize it.

Note that we don't need to repeat ourselves for the semiring and ring instances, since they all use the same definition of `*`/`1`/`^` so these lemmas match all three of them.
Does the linter complain if you mark this `simp`?
No, it doesn't.

Hi Eric! I see some of the error messages look like this:
```
error: SetLike.GradeZero.coe_natCast.{u_4, u_2, u_1} Left-hand side does not simplify, when using the simp lemma on itself.
```
Does it mean that I need to delete the `simp` tag of the theorems?

I'm a bit worried that these instances might be a bad idea; I'm not sure if lean actually has any way to infer `A`, and this might be the explanation for the simpNF failure and the other issues you saw before you moved the imports around.

Perhaps @vierkantor or @digama0 has opinions?

I can't reproduce the `simpNF` failure yet:
```lean
set_option trace.Meta.synthInstance true in
set_option trace.Meta.Tactic.simp true in
example (n : ℕ) : (n : A 0) = (n : R) := by simp only [coe_natCast]
```
succeeds, and the trace shows `  [] ✅ apply @SetLike.GradeZero.instSemiring to Semiring (↥A 0) ▶`. But yeah, it could very well turn out that the higher-order matching problem `A 0 = ?A 0` is too difficult.

The simpNF linter is still complaining about line 369 of this file even though the imports are now working. Would you be happy with them being local instances? At the end of the day, in algebraic geometry over a field, A 0 is typically that field. 

Perhaps another approach would be to assume that R is a comm ring, A is a graded R-algebra and the map R -> A identifies R with A 0; then one can work with R instead of A 0 and this is probably enough in applications I guess? Is there a natural Lean way of saying "I am a graded R-algebra and actually R is precisely my A 0?"

An easy way out is to write `GradeZero.subring A` instead of `A 0`, which definitely doesn't cause any instance issue.

I'm also happy with merging them as is, and revisiting it if/when we notice issues.

> Is there a natural Lean way of saying "I am a graded R-algebra and actually R is precisely my A 0?"

Not that I know of. We're also missing this case for "I am an R-algebra and actually my center is precisely R"
I've added some TODO comments warning about the unification performance here, I think it's then safe to merge as is.
So is this actually a bug in the simpNF linter which needs to be reported?
Yes, but I think it's not the only such one.

These should not be doc-comments; no one reading the docs cares about this.

```suggestion
  not simplify, when using the simp lemma on itself." is wrong. The LHS does simplify. -/
```

nodes.body: I have proved that for a Noetherian graded ring, its 0th grade is also a Noetherian ring.
@kbuzzard @eric-wieser

source.title: feat(Algebra/Module/GradeZeroModule): if `A` is a graded semiring and `M` is a graded `A`-module, then each grade of `M` is a module over the 0-th grade of `A`.

feat (RingTheory/GradedAlgebra/HomogeneousIdeal): given a finitely generated homogeneous ideal of a graded semiring, construct a finite spanning set for the ideal which only contains homogeneous elements
